<subSubSection id="4D3E82CB656A9F612AE66946C1175834" lastPageId="73" lastPageNumber="74" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" type="description">
<paragraph id="88CB95A56E5AA60BA4127115ECE7E15C" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="92E476431D36B5D563C724746A11FD81" lastPageId="73" lastPageNumber="74" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">
Shrubs 2-4 m tall with young tetragonal stems which become terete with age that are glabrescent to finely and sparsely furfuraceous; the nodal line present. Leaves of a pair equal to unequal in length. Petioles 0.4-1.2 cm. Leaf blades 
<pageBreakToken id="4D7BBCF69AEE729A6B18623CC82980F1" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" start="start">6</pageBreakToken>
-17 
<normalizedToken id="DB900F2A1C0323ADF416B05CB5BDF5EF" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
2-6 cm, 3-5 plinerved, with the innermost pair of veins diverging from the mid vein 1-2 cm above the base, elliptic, the base acute, the apex acute to acuminate, adaxially glabrous or sparsely ciliate, abaxially pubescent with stellate trichomes on the veins, the margins serrulate and ciliate. Inflorescence a terminal panicle 3-7 cm long branched above the base but sometimes appearing branched at the base because of multiple inflorescences arising at opposing meristems at the terminal node, accessory branches apparently absent, branches flattened; bracteoles linear to ovate, 2 mm long, early deciduous and appearing absent. Pedicels 2-5 mm. Flowers (5-)6-7 merous, calyptrate. Floral buds 10-15 
<normalizedToken id="A3DB043E976FF5B060B7C13D950B0E5D" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
4-7.1 mm, slightly ovoid to elliptic, subacute or rounded at the base, acute to acuminate at the apex, slightly constricted below the middle, the calyptra and base weakly differentiated; hypanthium 4.5-5.5 
<normalizedToken id="BC1E960BBD29DC6C72E0FFF1C111C64C" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
5-6 mm, glabrescent with inconspicuous sessile stellate hairs. Petals ca. 7-8 
<normalizedToken id="B12D1CB2B9DFB7B4F220E2282649456C" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
5-6 mm, white, broadly spatulate, probably spreading, glabrous. Stamens 15-20, 7 mm long, the filaments 3-4 mm long, white, anthers 3.5-4 mm long, linear-subulate, recurved, 
<pageBreakToken id="9437BABE9D968D65C17070A1D5C7C100" pageId="73" pageNumber="74" start="start">yellow</pageBreakToken>
, the pore not observed, terminal. Ovary 6-7 locular, inferior, glabrous, and elevated into a collar around the style base. Style 4-6 mm, curving and not widening below the stigma, bent beneath the tip, apparently no vertical or horizontal distance between the anthers and the stigma; stigma subcapitate, ca 1 mm wide. Mature berries not seen.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="DEE0D9889E3186C8B8B182F6053D0CC3" pageId="73" pageNumber="74" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="DD5006D334D8E323760153B4B8BF4562" pageId="73" pageNumber="74">Distribution</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8577DD507603416F0D0405FCFAE53640" pageId="73" pageNumber="74">
(Fig. 
<figureCitation id="E80E893601E77E78DB32FCF322A15A5B" captionStart="Figure 83" captionStartId="F83" captionText="Figure 83. Distribution of Conostegia jaliscana." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.67.6703.figure83" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/96441" pageId="73" pageNumber="74">83</figureCitation>
). Endemic to Mexico where it occurs in the Sierra Madre in the states of Jalisco and Guerrero from 700-1600 m in elevation.
</paragraph>
<caption id="44824EB8D0DF48DD8A0DA32C59C026F8" ID-Zenodo-Dep="974205" doi="10.3897/phytokeys.67.6703.figure83" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/96441" pageId="73" pageNumber="74" start="Figure 83" startId="F83">
<paragraph id="44F9526BD53BAF83F968FA9DE40F31C3" pageId="73" pageNumber="74">
<emphasis id="EEE8FD9D5C2535D1625474EFA4654990" bold="true" pageId="73" pageNumber="74">Figure 83.</emphasis>
Distribution of 
<taxonomicName id="3825618835A86C9570A76DFE17C76BE6" authority="Kriebel, 2016" authorityName="Kriebel" authorityYear="2016" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Conostegia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Conostegia jaliscana" order="Myrtales" pageId="73" pageNumber="74" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="jaliscana">
<emphasis id="F7E2768A7BC200E70D696038D8F8D083" italics="true" pageId="73" pageNumber="74">Conostegia jaliscana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="01378A6DBBEDF743E8277114CE094053" pageId="73" pageNumber="74">
<taxonomicName id="F102118CFEF72A36FF34204D62E1BAAD" authority="Kriebel, 2016" authorityName="Kriebel" authorityYear="2016" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Conostegia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Conostegia jaliscana" order="Myrtales" pageId="73" pageNumber="74" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="jaliscana">
<emphasis id="0B7D3382787CF7E8F11DE9E75138970B" italics="true" pageId="73" pageNumber="74">Conostegia jaliscana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a rare species reported usually from alongside streams. It has few-flowered inflorescences and relatively long and acute to acuminate floral buds. 
<bibRefCitation id="FB52D8A9C118534BEA0C04EBAD43355A" author="Schnell, CE" journalOrPublisher="Harvard University" pageId="243" pageNumber="244" refId="B77" refString="Schnell, CE, 1996. The Genus Conostegia (Melastomataceae). Harvard University" title="The Genus Conostegia (Melastomataceae)" year="1996">Schnell (1996)</bibRefCitation>
placed 
<taxonomicName id="548C27ABE1804B1E2DAC0C0A59EEC422" authority="Kriebel, 2016" authorityName="Kriebel" authorityYear="2016" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Conostegia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Conostegia jaliscana" order="Myrtales" pageId="73" pageNumber="74" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="jaliscana">
<emphasis id="DBFC362FF766C52AB181330B30298A9F" italics="true" pageId="73" pageNumber="74">Conostegia jaliscana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with the three Jamaican endemic in his section 
<taxonomicName id="69B342F906DCA17EB552E4EFC0FC3868" authority="Kriebel, 2016" authorityName="Kriebel" authorityYear="2016" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Conostegia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Myrtales" pageId="73" pageNumber="74" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="section" section="Conostegia">
<emphasis id="DEF921A24D7AC36B522B197DEAD52B5B" italics="true" pageId="73" pageNumber="74">Conostegia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but also hinted to the possibility of 
<taxonomicName id="141969D8923F25E253C7DC3CA407FE69" authority="Kriebel, 2016" authorityName="Kriebel" authorityYear="2016" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Conostegia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Conostegia jaliscana" order="Myrtales" pageId="73" pageNumber="74" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="jaliscana">
<emphasis id="2A00DCF7D8EF7A2682223FD6E5A89A80" italics="true" pageId="73" pageNumber="74">Conostegia jaliscana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
being closely related to species in his subgenus 
<taxonomicName id="3701EF2D40A50C0BA7EE576332E0D092" authority="Kriebel, 2016" authorityName="Kriebel" authorityYear="2016" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Conostegia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="(Lobatostigma)" order="Myrtales" pageId="73" pageNumber="74" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Lobatostigma">
<emphasis id="2A5F9FCC303AC3EE73883DEE4CAE00F4" italics="true" pageId="73" pageNumber="74">Lobatostigma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. This latter hypothesis is the one supported in the molecular phylogeny.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
